wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the cognitive-aware autonomous agent operating system. Explain its purpose as the world's first cognitive-aware agent OS, designed to coordinate AI agents across Executive, Technical, and Creative modes. Document the high-level architecture, including the C-suite agents (CEO Mimi, CTO Zara, CFO Maya, CLO Sage, CAO Eduardo) and managed ventures (LyricLines, Vision2Results, ModuMind, Ikidedventures). Describe the system's relationship between cognitive processing, blockchain DAO governance, and Akash Network infrastructure. Include both conceptual overviews for beginners and technical context for experienced developers. Use terminology consistent with the codebase such as 'orrery visualization', 'mode switching', and 'cognitive interface'. Provide practical examples of how the system enables AI-driven venture coordination. Address the rebranding from 371-OS to SynchroSource and its implications.

wiki_catalogs.name: Full-Stack Architecture
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the full-stack architecture of the cognitive-aware agent system. Describe the integration between Bun's embedded server and the React frontend, highlighting how server-side routing in index.tsx serves the client application. Explain the hybrid pattern where the same runtime handles both API endpoints and static asset delivery. Document the entry points: frontend.tsx initializing the React DOM and index.tsx booting the Bun server. Illustrate the request flow from client-side interactions to API responses via Hono-style routes. Include details on development features like HMR (Hot Module Replacement) enabled through Bun's development configuration. Provide a system context diagram showing the unified client-server process, and explain performance implications of this tight integration.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the frontend entry point defined in frontend.tsx. Explain how it serves as the bootstrap for the React application by mounting the App component to the DOM element with id 'root'. Document the use of React's StrictMode for development safety checks and the integration with Bun's hot module reloading (HMR) system through import.meta.hot. Provide examples of how the root is persisted during HMR to maintain state, and contrast this behavior with production where HMR is not available. Include best practices for modifying the entry point and common issues related to DOM element selection and hydration mismatches.

Address common issues such as text clipping on smaller screens and provide solutions using responsive classes. Explain integration points with the main orrery visualization and how the header maintains visual hierarchy.

Detail the route mapping strategy, including wildcard routing (/*) for frontend asset fallback and specific API endpoints. Explain how the development mode is detected and how HMR (Hot Module Replacement) and console echoing are conditionally enabled. Provide examples from the code showing the server instantiation and logging of the runtime URL. Address performance implications of Bun's native runtime and how configuration settings contribute to faster dependency resolution and testing cycles.

Address potential use cases such as client-side testing and service availability checks. Reference how this endpoint is consumed by the APITester component for interactive testing within the dashboard.

wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Overview: SynchroSource

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
SynchroSource is the world's first cognitive-aware autonomous agent operating system, designed to coordinate multiple AI agents across strategic, technical, and creative domains. Formerly known as 371-OS, this system provides a unified interface for managing AI-driven ventures through a dynamic, interactive dashboard.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Enable seamless coordination between specialized AI agents (CEO, CTO, CFO, CLO, CAO)
- Visualize real-time optimization metrics across operational modes
- Facilitate mode-switching between Executive, Technical, and Creative functions
- Integrate blockchain-based DAO governance and cost-optimized cloud infrastructure
- Provide an intuitive UI for monitoring agent performance and venture outcomes

### Target Audience
- AI system architects and developers
- Autonomous agent platform operators
- Decentralized organization (DAO) managers
- Cognitive computing researchers
- Enterprise AI solution designers

---

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The project follows a monorepo architecture with workspace support for modular scalability. Key components include:

- **Frontend Interface**: React-based dashboard with interactive orrery visualization
- **API Layer**: Embedded Bun server handling RESTful endpoints
- **State Management**: React hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`) for UI state
- **Visual Design**: Tailwind CSS with Lucide React icons and gradient effects
- **Runtime**: Built on Bun (v1.2.18), leveraging its high-performance JavaScript runtime

### Design Patterns
- **Component Composition**: Modular React components (App, APITester)
- **State-Driven UI**: Mode switching and hover interactions controlled via React state
- **CSS-in-JS with Tailwind**: Utility-first styling with dynamic class binding
- **Monorepo Structure**: Scalable architecture using `workspaces` in `package.json`

### System Relationships and Data Flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[Client Browser] --> B[Bun Server]
  B --> C[API Routes /api/*]
  C --> D[Response Generation]
  D --> E[JSON Data]
  E --> F[APITester Component]
  F --> G[UI Display]
  H[User Interaction] --> I[React State Update]
  I --> J[Dynamic UI Rendering]
  J --> A
```

---

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- **Frontend Entry**: `src/frontend.tsx` (referenced in `index.html`)
- **Server Entry**: `src/index.tsx` (Bun server with route definitions)
- **Root Component**: `AB/conceptual.md` (main App component with visualization)

### Core Modules
- `AB/conceptual.md`: Primary dashboard UI with agent orrery and mode switching
- `src/App.tsx`: Base application shell with logo and API tester integration
- `src/APITester.tsx`: Interactive API testing interface
- `src/index.tsx`: Backend server logic with routing

### Configuration Approach
- **TypeScript**: `tsconfig.json` with module resolution and path aliases (`@/*`)
- **Bun Runtime**: `bunfig.toml` for optimization and environment settings
- **Package Management**: `package.json` with Bun as package manager and workspace support
- **Build Scripts**: Development (`dev`), testing (`test`), linting (`lint`), and build (`build`)

### External Dependencies
- **hono**: Web framework for API routing
- **zod**: Schema validation (unused in current code but declared)
- **lucide-react**: Icon library
- **typescript**, **@types/node**: Development dependencies
- **biomejs/biome**: Linting tool

### Integration Points
- **API Gateway**: `/api/hello` and `/api/hello/:name` endpoints
- **Cloud Infrastructure**: Akash Network (97.6% cost reduction)
- **Governance Layer**: Blockchain DAO coordination
- **Runtime Environment**: Bun with HMR (Hot Module Replacement) in development

### Component Relationship Diagram

```mermaid
graph TD
  A[Browser] --> B(index.html)
  B --> C(frontend.tsx)
  C --> D(App Component)
  D --> E[Orrery Visualization]
  D --> F[Mode Switcher]
  D --> G[Agent Tooltip]
  D --> H[APITester]
  H --> I[Form Input]
  I --> J[Fetch API]
  J --> K[Bun Server]
  K --> L[/api/hello*]
  L --> M[JSON Response]
  M --> H
```

---

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
- **Interactive Orrery**: Animated visualization of C-suite agents and ventures
- **Mode Switching**: Toggle between Executive, Technical, and Creative modes
- **Agent Hover Tooltips**: Real-time performance metrics on hover
- **API Testing Panel**: Built-in endpoint tester with method selection
- **Embedded Server**: Bun-powered backend with route handling
- **Cost-Optimized Infrastructure**: Akash Network integration

### Implementation Highlights
- Dynamic mode styling using Tailwind classes bound to state
- Circular layout via CSS transforms and trigonometric positioning
- Pulse animation on core cognitive interface
- Responsive tooltip with optimization progress bar
- Form-driven API interaction with JSON response display

### Feature Architecture: Agent Coordination System

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
  [*] --> DashboardLoaded
  DashboardLoaded --> ExecutiveMode: Default
  ExecutiveMode --> TechnicalMode: User Click
  TechnicalMode --> CreativeMode: User Click
  CreativeMode --> ExecutiveMode: User Click
  ExecutiveMode --> AgentHovered: Mouse Enter
  AgentHovered --> TooltipDisplayed: Render Info
  TooltipDisplayed --> AgentUnhovered: Mouse Leave
  AgentUnhovered --> ExecutiveMode: Hide Tooltip
  ExecutiveMode --> ModeChanged: Button Click
  ModeChanged --> NewMode: Update State
  NewMode --> DashboardUpdated: Re-render UI
```

### Dependency Diagram

```mermaid
graph TD
  A[SynchroSource] --> B[React 19]
  A --> C[Bun Runtime]
  A --> D[TypeScript]
  B --> E[Lucide React Icons]
  C --> F[Hono Framework]
  D --> G[tsup Builder]
  A --> H[Tailwind CSS]
  A --> I[Akash Network]
  A --> J[Blockchain DAO]
```

---

## Conclusion

SynchroSource represents a novel approach to autonomous agent orchestration, combining real-time visualization with cognitive mode switching and decentralized governance. The architecture leverages modern tools like Bun and React 19 to deliver a high-performance, interactive dashboard for managing AI-driven ventures.

While the current implementation focuses on the frontend visualization and basic API testing, the monorepo structure and workspace configuration indicate plans for significant expansion into agent coordination protocols, venture modules, and advanced cognitive processing capabilities.

Sources:
- [projectinfo.md](projectinfo.md)
- [conceptual.md](AB/conceptual.md)
- [index.tsx](src/index.tsx)
- [App.tsx](src/App.tsx)
- [APITester.tsx](src/APITester.tsx)
- [package.json](package.json)
- [tsconfig.json](tsconfig.json)
- [bunfig.toml](bunfig.toml)
</blog>
